2ade6205-d2b2-48e8-b7ef-f19298b345f4.04b78b9a-a5e5-4ca3-9cf9-5ac0980b0253.prompt=VMWare User\: 2ade6205-d2b2-48e8-b7ef-f19298b345f4.0956668e-1bf4-4d03-84b6-bcc4d49aa34a.description=
Search for VMWare objects of type propsType and their properties (propsPathset) from a root object (if any) specified by propsRootObjType and propsRootObj. Retrieve each object's properties one at a time from an initial search query ala SQL Query operation. Please see VMWare Integration Guide for more details.

Inputs\:
host - VMWare host hostname or IP.
user - VMWare username.
password - VMWare user's password.
port - Port to connect on.
protocol - Connection protocol (http or https).
closeSession - Close the internally kept VMWare Infrastructure API session at completion of operation (true, false).
propsType - VMWare properties type (Task, Datacenter, VirtualMachine, Network etc.) to filter on. Type of object results desired.
propsPathset - Property filter's pathset, comma-delimited (eg. name, info.name, runtime.host).
propsRootObjType - The type of the Managed Object Reference (such as VirtualMachine, HostSystem, ComputeResource, ResourcePool, Alarm, Datacenter, Datastore) to begin the search on. Leaving this blank will default the root object to the root folder of the ESX or VC host. 
propsRootObj - The value of the reference (such as vm-123, datastore-123, network-123) used as a root object. Leaving this blank will default the root object to be the root folder of the ESX or VC host. 

Responses\:
success - The operation completed successfully.
failure - Something went wrong. See returnResult for details.
no more - There are no more results to retrieve.

Returns\:
numberOfResults - Number of results from the query remaining to be retrieved.
returnResult - Query result item or reason for failure.

2ade6205-d2b2-48e8-b7ef-f19298b345f4.74c6fef9-51fc-4ea8-8863-50c402305b23.prompt=Enter a value for value2 2ade6205-d2b2-48e8-b7ef-f19298b345f4.7824698a-01a2-48fa-98e1-f556dd3e9b90.prompt=Enter a value for value1 2ade6205-d2b2-48e8-b7ef-f19298b345f4.8211bc71-968c-4975-bc67-c29050e3ddb5.description=
Compares two strings, returning a true response if and only if they contain the same sequence of characters. A null string is considered to be equal to an empty string.

Inputs\:
string1 - The first string.
string2 - The second string.
ignoreCase - If set to 'true', then the comparison ignores case considerations. The two strings are considered equal ignoring case if they are of the same length and corresponding characters in the two strings are equal ignoring case. If set to any value other than 'true', then the strings must match exactly to be considered equal.

responses\:
true - If the two strings are equal
false - If the two strings are not equal

2ade6205-d2b2-48e8-b7ef-f19298b345f4.cffae1c6-5588-4d83-b19c-5393ec726d77.prompt=Enter a value for value1 2ade6205-d2b2-48e8-b7ef-f19298b345f4.d4f7527a-36a9-4cd7-ab6a-cbe5de09adb5.prompt=Enter a value for value1 2ade6205-d2b2-48e8-b7ef-f19298b345f4.description=
Retrieve CPU and Memory Compute available capacity from a vCenter instance 

Description\: This flow contacts the vCenter instance with the host and credentials provided, and begins by retrieving Datacenters.  If our Resource Pool reference (The "Known by Provider As" value) is the name of a Data Center, then we iterate through the hostFolder of the datacenter to summarize each of the compute resources. For each resource, we retrieve the number of CPU cores available, and the total available memory.  We aggregate these values for the entire datacenter, and convert the value for memory from bytes to megabytes before returning both values from the subflow.

If our pool reference is not a Datacenter, then we will iterate through the current datacenter to determine if our pool reference is a cluster, or an individual host.  If we match our pool reference, we set our two available values, convert bytes to megabytes, and exit the flow.  If we don't find our resource pool reference in this datacenter, we return to continue to iterate through all available datacenters until we find it.

If we do not find a match for our pool reference at all , then we exit with a "resource not found" error.



Input Parameters\:

host - the vCenter host instance
user - The vCenter instance access credentials
password - The vCenter instance access credentials
poolReference - the Resource Pool Name ("Known by Provider As"), passed into the subflow
 
Responses\:
 success - The operation completed successfully.
 failure - An operation or subflow failed to execute normally.
